segments.text: You were talking about the areas of emphasis, I believe.
And this was reflected in, as you would imagine, in large measure by the people who were here and those we recruited early on.
Silver culture was certainly something that we emphasized.
We had strengths in soils.

And this is another example of why you can build strong programs at Texas A&M because not only did we have strength in soils, but we also could draw on the soil and crop sciences department for strength over there as well.
You could say the same thing about economics and so on, because forestry, like most of those kind of fields, are made up of a group of disciplines.
And so you hear faculty come to you trained in the discipline with an application to forestry.
Silver culture soils, our investment in wood technology was in wood chemistry.
If you go toward solid wood research and this sort of thing, it gets to be terribly expensive.
So we hired a wood chemist, Dr. Goldstein, to lead that effort.
And he did extremely well.
And again, related to other chemists on the campus who had a common interest in cellulose chemistry.
It took a while for, except for the people that were already established, it took a while for us to develop areas of emphasis.
The evolution of a new department and new faculty is such that they spend their early years getting their teaching programs established because those students show up every day.
And this slows down the process in research a bit.
But ultimately, they come on and get a research program started and go on from there.
What were some of the first signals to you as their leader that you were having some success?
Well, I guess the first one was we applied for and gained accreditation for our program by the Society of American Foresters in the minimum time required, which was five years.
The society has been accrediting
forestry education program since 1935 and has a long-standing relationship with helping with this national accrediting organization.
Anyway, it's a member of that.
A lot of academic programs have attempted to get into the accreditation business, and they lack standards and everything that goes with the accreditation process.
But SAF has been in the business a long time, so we felt that was our first major
In this part of the world, then Stephen F. Austin, LSU, Arkansas Monticello, Oklahoma State, then Mississippi State, Tennessee.
Auburn, Georgia, Florida, North Carolina State, DPI.
Do you have any idea how many nationally?
Yeah.
And I presume as the years have gone on, there haven't been any particular problems of retaining that presentation.
No, there have not.
And as you can imagine, there's a continuing debate within the...
Society of American Foragers about what accreditation ought to be.
And everybody seems to have a different opinion about that.
But no, we've not had any trouble with that.
What about some important early faculty accomplishments, recognitions, grants, et cetera?
Winning national awards.
Well, I don't know how much claim we can make here because some of the more senior faculty that we recruited had already, Goldstein, again, as an example, has already established himself.
And of course, we are like the bird hunter.
We claim all the birds that fall, but Irv got some
good national awards in the 70s, I guess.
Dave Boring, of course, who was here when we started, received awards in soils.
I'm drawing a blank on anybody else right now.
In seeking...
off-campus funding, where does the person in forest return primarily for submission ?
Well, in that period of time, you primarily

went to industry for your off-campus funding, although there were some, well, the U.S. Forest Service had funding through its research arm that you could gain access to, and we were successful there in some cases.
but primarily industry and the federal system.
And, of course, then you always try to get the director of the experiment station to include something in his legislative budget request that would be helpful to you.
Which industries, looking back over this 30 years,
Which industries have been supportive that you would like to mention?
Well, Temple, which is now Temple Inland, but I've gone through a series of different kind of ownerships.
continues today to be supportive, and it's, as you know, has family ties to East Texas.
They've been also very supportive of Stephen F. Austin, too.
Arthur tends to be fairly provincial in his view.
and wants to make sure his money stays in East Texas and doesn't cross the Trinity River.
But the company itself has been very supportive.
Kirby, which is now Louisiana Pacific, was helpful to us in the early going.
Owens, Illinois, which is now
Champion International, St. Regis, Southland Paper Company, Melvin Kirk, Kirk family, and they helped us in different ways.
We largely approached the earth planning.
In fact, we still have a Southwest scholarship that started way back in the primary in the current planning.
In terms of students, about what was the enrollment of people planning for as far as their careers in the .
Oh.
I'd say maybe 20.
What we did was, of course, when the word got out that we were going to have a forestry department offer a U.S. degree, then those people who were coming here for the two-year program
you know, shifted gears and stayed with us.
But my guess is the first bunch amounted to about 20 or something like that.
By the time when the program is fully approved, do you remember what the enrollment might have been about that time?
Oh, by the coordinating board.
Probably not much more.
Were there any important landmarks such as when the first forestry undergraduate degree was granted?
Yeah.
Of course, that was granted in one of our
two-year people who were here in this state.
And so I think the first actual degree we granted was in 1971.
Yeah, 1971, because the department was started in 69.
So I think in two years, we'll be getting our first degree.
And we also had a cadre of graduate students that had been here.
One who used to be on our faculty, got his PhD here very early on.
And so I guess
probably we had 10 or 15 graduate students when we got started.
But they had come, one, either to work on the PhD, but we had already been granted that authority, or started .
Do you remember when the first PhD was granted?
No, I don't.
It was after you arrived, though?
Well, as you can imagine, we get quite a number out of East Texas.
As the years have passed, they come more out of the urban centers.
And it's not unusual to get them out of West Texas, Fort Stockton or someplace like that.
But right now, the urban areas
And very good students.
By the time you got here, women had already been admitted to the university.
Were the women in the forestry program early?
Not early.
Not early.
Although, with time, we've had a good number
students, both graduate students and undergraduates.
I was talking to one the other day who's the new head of the department at Clemson University.
A graduate of A&M?
Yes.
What's her name?
Pat.
You'll remember when you were raised by Howard.
That's always an interesting process on this campus.
We were, of course, came out of the Range Science Department.
And so, Harry Kirkall had worked out an arrangement for us

move from the second floor to the third floor in what's now the Peterson Building, which was Plant Sciences then, and occupy some space along the horticulture, and maybe retain a little space in Range Science.
I'm not exactly sure how that worked, but we got our offices
away from the brain science department and onto the third floor of Peterson.
And they were quite modest, I might add.
But we did keep the labs that we had down in the building.
And very soon,
We got enough money put together to build what's called a forest science lab out on Agronomy Road now, right next to purchasing and stores.
Then go forward chronologically.
Where did you move to after this first year?
We thought we had died and gone to heaven.
when the recreation and parks department moved out of the old horse barn.
And we were given that building.
And we thought that was absolutely wonderful.
That was about 1972.
And so it did give us adequate
office, administrative space, some teaching space.
But we still, for that time, we had the forest science lab out on the west campus.
So we had four big research labs out there and some office space.
So we were pretty good here based on the number of people we had.
Of course, a lot of the research then
and now to some degree is conducted in East Texas field research.
What locations?
Well, mostly on industry land.
We had research located on companies that I named a while ago, work out an arrangement with them to set aside particular areas that had the kind of

forest and they were very in fact I just sat in on a meeting day before yesterday that will involve seven companies not just in Texas but in Louisiana and Arkansas that will involve that sort of thing and they will commit resources and people
Now, most of this of the apartments for service, most of it is on the growing of the tree, or is it on the processing and the chemistry of the tree that is already there?
Most of it is on what we would call forest production, the growing and culture of forest stands.
Although we have had, I mentioned Goldstein.
Later on, we hired a guy by the name of Joe Massey, who was an operations research guy.
He did an awful lot of work in temple's mills on how they ought to position their making their plywood and that sort of thing and optimizing their mill operations.
And so Joe was here, gosh, 20 years or so and made a
very significant impact with his research.
So that most of it has to do with the pine trees.
Yes.
And the processing of the trees.
And some of the cabin maker, as a little kid, remember, he was doing a lot of work with the cyclists, which almost no longer is processed in the country, but they do it all the time.
No, most of the hardwood that's cut today will go into pulp and paper.
That's a desired
They have desired characteristics for that fine paper business.
Except for the river bottoms in Texas, the quality of the hardwoods is not very good.
Not like you run into over in the Carolinas and North Georgia and that part of the world.
Let's jump back to your new service department head, Henry.
Well, you know, happily, most of it were joys.
Obviously, the typical frustrations come along on personnel issues and this sort of thing, funding, this sort of thing.
But generally, I got good support from the college dean's office.
Harry was a good dean.
Well, Harry had a...
First of all, Harry was a scientist, so he understood where science fit in the overall scheme of things in an academic setting.
But secondly, he also knew what it took to make a department successful.
And he was accessible, easy to talk to,
And I found him to be a very good boss.
And then I ran into you in that period of time, because somewhere along in there, when you became dean of faculties, we used to have to bring every faculty candidate
that we were interviewing to your office.
And I have, later on, I filched a lot of your techniques that I saw you use during that interview process.
Because one of the things that you did was share with those faculty members or those candidates
a lot of
It's something that changes paths.
We are conservative students.
We're changing, but we don't change the fact that we kind of follow the tradition of the world.
And I remember one fellow who was from Berkeley who looked like a smelly one, but he acted like it.
And he came back the next day and thanked me.
And he said, I don't really like it here very much.
And I said, no, you all wouldn't like me.
Well, his role was most pronounced when we were starting.
I mean, every time that we had a critical
moved to make, you know, he was there, he was supportive, and offered good advice about how to do things and that sort of thing.
And then early on when we started, he helped sweep the money together to get that building out there.
And so we'd have a place to do some research and that sort of thing.
So I'd say his impact was greatest in the early years of my tenure as department head.
I found him to be just super, and then later when I moved over to the experiment station and started having a different kind of relationship with him, I tended to appreciate him even more.
because, you know, we'd have the usual problems with personnel and funding and that sort of thing that we had to work out.
And he was just always a super guy to try to work with.
You were supported originally to have them to couple.
Patterson was gone by the time I actually moved here.
So you started out reporting to Harry, and the whole eight years he was redeemed?
Right.
Did you also report either to the Experiment Station or Extension Service?
Well, yes, certainly the Experiment Station.
Jarvis Miller was involved there.
toward the latter part of that period of time.
He was associate director for a while and then he became director.
John Hutchison was director of extension.
Yeah, you could say I reported to him, but we had, as every department head did, except for maybe a few like Ty Timm,
had a very different relationship than we had with Jarvis or Harry.
John was a very dominant personality and there wasn't much give or take there.
And we didn't have the budgetary and administrative relationship with Extension at that time that they do now.

In general percentages, about what percentage of the department's budget during those years came from the academic, what percentage from the experiment station, what percentage from the extension service?
I'd say probably 60% in the early years was from the academic side.
30% from Experiment Station and 10% from Extension.
We didn't have but one Extension specialist.
Did that change by the end of your eight years?
Yes.
How so?
The Experiment Station became a bigger player.
Extension never really changed during my tenure there.
All that came later.
but we began to bring in more researchers.
Did you, as you had your own personal set of goals for the department, did you win, did you achieve every goal, or were there some where you were frustrated?
Well, your ambitions are always fairly substantially beyond your ability to accomplish, but I'd say
We set out as our first goal to become accredited, and we achieved that in a timely way.
I think probably I had two disappointments.
Our enrollment did not grow as fast as I thought it should.
And I thought our research program would probably go faster and larger than it did.
But other than that, I think the eight years I spent were quite rewarding.
Were there impediments on campus to either of those goals, enrollment and research?
Were there any handicaps?
Not really that the institution imposed.
I think, you know, in most cases, we tend to,
Those sort of limitations tend to be self-imposed for one reason or the other.
So I always viewed the institution as one of our real strengths.
As you look back on those years, what were the key courses
that a forest science major took either in the department or out of it?
There must have been some key courses that were submitted.
Well, obviously the first two years are a fairly common set of courses that
either by requirement or whatever everybody takes, and certainly it's the case now with the core curriculum.
But we had a core curriculum that was more on a departmental level than it was on an institutional level.
I'd say once the student got beyond the
the sophomore year.
